'''Project Deep Spill''' was the first intentional deepwater [[oil spill]], in order to study how crude oil behaved in-depth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE65D3Z220100614|title=Special Report: Deepwater spills and short attention spans|last=Robert Campbell|first=Robert Campbell|date=14 June 2010|publisher=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=21 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=377-Project "Deep Spill"|url=http://www.mms.gov/tarprojects/377.htm|date=24 March 2005|publisher=[[Minerals Management Service]]|accessdate=21 June 2010}}</ref> A [[Joint Industry Project]] comprising 23 oil companies and the [[Minerals Management Service]] performed a sea trial in late June 2000 in the Helland Hansen region of the [[Norwegian Sea]]. The trial made several releases of varying combinations of crude oil (750 barrels), marine diesel, methane (18 cubic metres) and nitrogen gas from the seabed at 840 metres below sea-level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mms.gov/tarprojects/377/DeepSpill%20Final%20Report.pdf|title=DEEP SPILL JIP EXPERIMENTAL DISCHARGES OF GAS AND OIL AT HELLAND HANSEN – JUNE 2000, TECHNICAL REPORT|last=Johansen|first=Øistein|author2=Henrik Rye |author3=Alf G. Melbye |author4=Hans V. Jensen |author5=Bjørn Serigstad |author6=Tor Knutsen |date=2001-06-05|work=[[SINTEF]] REPORT|accessdate=21 June 2010|location=Norway}}</ref>
